snippet.textDisplay: Has anyone asked to buy the battery powered welder you just built?  It may be a lame lightsaber but could be handy for remote field welders. In a serious note though, could the "rod" one day be thin as a string and coiled inside handle, propelled out and stiffened when powered to create a lightweight form of rod that emits the same amount of heat and power?   I wonder if you guys play around with materials for the string (or superheated rod) and using conventional 240v power source from the wall, maybe lightsabers won't seem so far fetched.  Obviously the hand-sized power source is something not yet possible.

snippet.textDisplay: Ok, on a serious note, if/when we create usable lightsabers (or something close enough to a lightsaber), do you think it will be used as a weapon or used as a tool for cutting through some materials? I mean, in my head canon, our future real  life lightsaber can cut through things (like a saber) but doesn’t deflect bullets or whatnot (cuz a beam of heat doesn’t really deflect things, I don’t think at least). So we have a beam of heat that can cut through materials and can be used offensively or as a tool. I think it would be cool to see them used as industrial tools that can speed up processes of cutting dense materials. I’m no scientist so I have no idea if what I said is possible or accurate. Either way, we all can agree a real life lightsaber is pretty dang cool, no matter how impractical it may be.
